\title{Inductive hypothesis}

\p{The \em{inductive hypothesis} in an inductive proof is the assumption made in the
inductive case that a property #{P} we wish to prove holds for #{E} \em{already} holds for
some component or subordinate case that #{E} depends on.}

\p{For example, #{E} may be an arithmetic sum while a component might be a term #{t_i} in
#{E}. We then seek to show that if #{P} holds for every #{t_i} in #{E}, then it also holds
for #{E}. Together with a base case, we prove that #{P} holds for #{E}.}
